        "-200": "Cisalpine Gaul falls under Roman control as the Republic expands northward, establishing Latin colonies in the Po valley and slowly Romanizing the Celtic populations, while beyond the Alps, Transalpine Gaul remains independent though increasingly drawn into Mediterranean politics, some tribes allying with Rome against rivals, others resisting Roman interference, the Aedui becoming Rome's 'friends and allies' in arrangements that prefigure full conquest.",
        "-100": "Julius Caesar's Gallic Wars brutally subjugate Transalpine Gaul over eight years of campaigning—Vercingetorix's doomed rebellion at Alesia symbolizing Gaulish resistance crushed by Roman discipline—while Caesar's Commentaries justify the conquest as defensive yet transparently advertise his military genius to Roman audiences, the war's end leaving perhaps a million dead and another million enslaved, Gaul now a Roman province whose wealth will fund civil wars and imperial splendor.",
        "0": "Roman Gaul prospers under the Pax Augusta as cities develop with forums, amphitheaters, and baths, Latin replaces Gaulish among urban elites while countryside populations maintain Celtic language and customs, the Rhine frontier heavily militarized against Germanic threats, yet Gaul's integration into the empire seems secure as Gaulish aristocrats enter the Roman senate and emperors recruit legions from Gallic populations whose martial traditions now serve Rome rather than resist it.",
        "100": "The apogee of Roman Gaul sees thriving cities like Lugdunum (Lyon), Burdigala (Bordeaux), and Lutetia (Paris) adorned with monumental architecture, while villa estates spread across the countryside producing grain, wine, and garum for empire-wide trade, Christianity begins spreading through urban communities though traditional Celtic and Roman paganism remain dominant, the province's prosperity seemingly guaranteed by Roman power even as Germanic pressure on the Rhine frontier slowly intensifies.",
        "200": "Roman Gaul maintains its prosperity despite occasional Germanic incursions across the Rhine, Gaulish legions playing crucial roles in imperial civil wars while the province's cities continue flourishing, villa agriculture reaches its zenith, and pottery workshops at La Graufesenque export terra sigillata across the empire, though economic patterns begin shifting as taxation increases and urban populations start declining, presaging the troubles that will convulse the third-century empire.",
        "300": "The empire's crisis has passed but transformed Gaul as Germanic tribes settle as foederati within imperial frontiers, Christianity spreads through St. Martin's missionary efforts while pagan shrines close, villa estates grow more self-sufficient as long-distance trade declines, and urban populations shrink behind hastily erected walls, barbarian generals commanding Roman armies in the emperor's name while maintaining Germanic cultural identities, the classical world's structures persisting yet hollowed from within.",
        "400": "Roman Gaul collapses as Germanic tribes settle. The Franks emerge as the dominant power, blending Roman and Germanic traditions under the Merovingian dynasty.",
        500: "Clovis unites the Frankish tribes and converts to Catholic Christianity. The Merovingian kingdom expands but gradually weakens as mayors of the palace gain real power.",
