        "-1000": "Phoenician traders establish coastal colonies including Cádiz, bringing eastern Mediterranean influence. Celtic and Iberian tribes control the interior, developing distinct cultures.",
        "-600": "Phoenician Gadir (Cádiz) thrives as a trading hub extracting silver from Iberian mines while Greek colonists establish Emporion on the northeast coast, both Mediterranean powers competing for access to the peninsula's mineral wealth, yet neither penetrating far inland where Celtic Celtiberians and Iberians maintain independent warrior societies centered on hilltop oppida, their fierce resistance to foreign encroachment becoming legendary even as coastal populations adopt Phoenician and Greek cultural practices.",
        "-500": "Carthaginian power expands in southern Iberia following Phoenicia's decline, Carthaginian generals exploiting silver mines to fund Mediterranean wars while recruiting Iberian mercenaries renowned for their lethal falcatas and effective guerrilla tactics, the indigenous population divided between those benefiting from Punic trade and those resisting foreign domination, Celtic migrations from across the Pyrenees adding further complexity to the peninsula's ethnic and political landscape.",
        "-400": "Celtic and Iberian cultures blend in the interior creating the Celtiberian synthesis, their fortified hilltop towns controlling agricultural valleys while Carthaginian influence intensifies along southern and eastern coasts, Iberian sculpture reaches sophisticated heights with works like the Lady of Elche, yet no unified resistance emerges against Carthaginian expansion, tribal divisions and endemic warfare preventing pan-Iberian political organization that might resist Mediterranean imperialism.",
